{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17575416","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17575416"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T02:39:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T02:39:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"24031"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"24031","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/24031"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.31,0.08,0.07,0.22,0.31]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"16886"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116323"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"16886","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/16886"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"24031"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98319"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"22"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1223"},{"type":"tags","id":"1353"},{"type":"tags","id":"1627"},{"type":"tags","id":"2371"},{"type":"tags","id":"4985"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"12227"},{"type":"tags","id":"12926"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"49925"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116323","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/116323"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a 12-month history of irregular periods occurring every two to three months. She is not currently trying to conceive but is concerned about her menstrual irregularity. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her BMI is 23 kg/m\u00b2. There is no evidence of hirsutism, acne, or acanthosis nigricans. Abdominal and pelvic examinations are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most appropriate to confirm the diagnosis of polycystic ovary syndrome?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone level","Thyroid stimulating hormone","Prolactin level","Fasting insulin level","17-hydroxyprogesterone"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EPolycystic ovary syndrome (PCOS) is diagnosed using the Rotterdam criteria, which requires two out of three of the following: oligomenorrhoea or secondary amenorrhoea, clinical or biochemical hyperandrogenism, and polycystic ovarian morphology (PCOM). This patient presents with oligomenorrhoea (irregular periods every two to three months), fulfilling one criterion. Without clinical signs of hyperandrogenism, further investigation is needed to establish whether she meets the diagnostic criteria for PCOS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-M\u00fcllerian hormone level\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate investigation to confirm the diagnosis. According to current guidelines, serum AMH can be used as an alternative to ultrasound to define polycystic ovarian morphology in adults. An elevated AMH level would indicate PCOM, providing the second criterion needed for PCOS diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid stimulating hormone\u003C/strong\u003E should be checked to exclude thyroid dysfunction as a cause of menstrual irregularity, but it would not confirm a diagnosis of PCOS. Thyroid disorders can mimic PCOS symptoms and should be ruled out as part of the differential diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProlactin level\u003C/strong\u003E is important to exclude hyperprolactinaemia as a cause of oligomenorrhoea, but like TSH, it would not confirm PCOS. Elevated prolactin can cause menstrual irregularity and should be excluded before diagnosing PCOS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFasting insulin level\u003C/strong\u003E may be elevated in women with PCOS who have insulin resistance, but it is not part of the diagnostic criteria for PCOS. While insulin resistance is common in PCOS, it is not required for diagnosis and would not confirm the condition.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003E17-hydroxyprogesterone\u003C/strong\u003E is used to exclude non-classical congenital adrenal hyperplasia, which can present similarly to PCOS. While it may be part of the workup to exclude other causes, it would not confirm the diagnosis of PCOS.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIt\u0027s important to note that AMH should not be used as a single test for PCOS diagnosis but rather as part of the diagnostic algorithm. In this case, with oligomenorrhoea already present, an elevated AMH indicating PCOM would fulfil the second criterion needed for diagnosis according to the Rotterdam criteria.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Anti-M\u00fcllerian hormone (AMH) can be used as an alternative to ultrasound to assess for polycystic ovarian morphology when only one Rotterdam criterion is present.","The Rotterdam criteria require 2 out of 3 features for PCOS diagnosis: oligo/anovulation, clinical/biochemical hyperandrogenism, and polycystic ovarian morphology."],"references":["Monash Centre for Health Research and Implementation. PCOS practice tools for health practitioners [Internet]. Clayton (VIC): Monash University; [cited 2025 Aug 24]. Available from: https://mchri.org.au/guidelines-resources/health-professionals/pcos-practice-tools/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98319"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"24031"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"98319","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/98319"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-09-28T13:37:12+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-28T13:42:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"16886"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"116323"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"22","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/22"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf53","name":"Gynaecology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"3"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"d